http__purl_org_dc_terms_description: These terms are related to how an organism ecologically interacts with other organisms, whether it is free living or symbiotic (e.g. parasitic).

http__www_w3_org_2004_02_skos_core_defin: The photosynthetic partner is a green algae, and specifically a Chlorophyta.
Organism hosts phototropic partner.
A commensal symbiont that lives inside of its host.
Organism hosts phototropic partner under some circumstances, but not obligately.

Participating in symbiosis. Symbiosis is the living together of two organisms; the relationship between two interacting organisms or populations, commonly used to describe all relationships between members of two different species, and also to include intraspecific associations; sometimes restricted to those associations that are mutually beneficial.
Species that removes ectoparasites, diseased and injured tissue, and unwanted food particles from a client (host).
Species which is suspected to take part in a symbiotic relation, but without real observations.
Decorating (hooked setae modification).
Co-habiting as ectosymbiont.
Organism does not host phototropic partner.
A mutualistic relationship where one organism lives on the outer surface of another organism.
Symbiosis in which a bacterium provides chemically-derived energy and nutrients.
Carrying for camouflage (pereiopod modification).

Any organism that is intimately associated with, and metabolically dependent upon another living organism (the host) for completion of its life cycle, and which is typically detrimental to the host to a greater or lesser extent.
The photosynthetic partner is unknown.
A parasite that lives on the outer surface of its host, ectosite; epiparasite; episite; exoparasite; cf. endoparasite.
Participating in commensalism. Commensalism is symbiosis in which one species derives benefit from a common food supply whilst the other species is not adversely affected.
Co-habiting as endosymbiont.
The photosynthetic partner is a Cyanobacteria.
The photosynthetic partner is unknown.
A type of parasite intermediate between ecto- and endoparasites.
Organism hosts phototropic partner, obligately.
A commensal symbiont living on the surface of another organism.
A mutualistic relationship where one organism lives within the body or cells of another organism.
The photosynthetic partner is a dinoflagellate.
Carrying for shelter (pereiopod and/or abdomen modification).
It is unknown whether or not the organism hosts a phototrophic partner.
The photosynthetic partner is a green algae, and specifically a Chlorophyta.
Special case of symbiosis in which both partners benefit from the association.
It is unknown whether or not the organism hosts a phototrophic partner.
Species which is not known or suspected to take part in a symbiotic relationship.
An internal parasite which lives within the organs or tissues of its host; endosite; entoparasite; cf. ectoparasite.
The photosynthetic partner is a dinoflagellate.
Inquilism (dwelling within inanimate cavities, such as burrows and tubes in soft sediment, where the host may or may not be present).
The photosynthetic partner is a Cyanobacteria.
